## OPTION 1: Classic Positioning Framework

**Choose this if:** Established category, clear competitors, differentiation is HOW you do it

### The 7 Positioning Strategies

**Which strategy are you using?** (Choose ONE - don't try multiple)

#### 1. Leadership Positioning
**Claim:** "We're #1 in [category/metric]"

**When to use:**
- You genuinely are the market leader
- You have data proving leadership
- Category is established and customers care about being with the leader

**Examples:**
- ✅ "Most-used workspace for remote teams" (if true)
- ✅ "#1 rated for ease of use on G2"
- ❌ "Industry-leading solution" (vague, no proof)

**What you need:**
- Third-party validation (G2, Gartner, market share data)
- Specific metric you lead in
- Proof competitors can't credibly dispute

---

#### 2. Attribute Ownership
**Claim:** "We own [attribute]" (fastest, easiest, most secure)

**When to use:**
- You can credibly claim and defend a valuable attribute
- Competitors haven't claimed it
- The attribute matters to your target segment

**Examples:**
- ✅ "Fastest to implement - live in 48 hours"
- ✅ "Easiest to use - no training required"
- ❌ "Most innovative" (vague, unownable)

**What you need:**
- Data proving you're meaningfully better
- Attribute must be important to customers
- Ability to defend against competitors

**Example (Notion SMB):** "Fastest to implement" - 2 hours vs Confluence 2 weeks (G2 data)

---

#### 3. Specialization Positioning
**Claim:** "We're the only [product] built specifically for [narrow audience/use case]"

**When to use:**
- You can't win broad market leadership
- You serve a niche better than generalists
- Niche is large enough to build a business

**Examples:**
- ✅ "Only workspace built for product teams under 50"
- ✅ "Project management designed exclusively for creative agencies"
- ❌ "Best tool for everyone" (too broad)

**What you need:**
- Features/workflow specific to the niche
- Proof generalists don't serve this niche well
- Willingness to say NO to customers outside the niche

---

#### 4. Heritage Positioning
**Claim:** "We were the first to do [innovation]" or "We've been doing [X] since [year]"

**When to use:**
- You pioneered a category or feature
- Longevity/experience matters to customers
- Being "first" creates credibility

**Examples:**
- ✅ "Invented the blocks-based workspace in 2016"
- ✅ "25 years securing enterprise data"
- ❌ "Innovative newcomer" (contradicts heritage)

---

#### 5. Against-the-Leader Positioning
**Claim:** "Unlike [market leader], we [key difference]"

**When to use:**
- You're NOT the leader but have clear advantage
- Leader has known weakness you exploit
- Customers are frustrated with the leader

**Examples:**
- ✅ "Unlike Salesforce, we're built for teams under 50 - setup in hours, not months"
- ✅ "Unlike [competitor], we don't charge per user - unlimited team members"
- ❌ "Better than [competitor]" (vague, not specific)

**What you need:**
- Clear understanding of leader's weakness
- Your strength directly counters their weakness
- Proof customers care about this difference

**Example (Notion SMB):** "Unlike Confluence, no IT setup required - your team can start today"

---

#### 6. Re-positioning the Competition
**Claim:** Position competitor negatively to make your advantage clear

**When to use:**
- Competitor's strength is actually a weakness
- You can reframe the market to your advantage
- Direct comparison highlights your benefit

**Examples:**
- ✅ "Other tools force you to choose: wiki OR tasks OR docs. We're all three."
- ✅ "Complex tools require training. Simple tools lack power. We're both powerful AND simple."
- ❌ "Competitors are bad" (negative, not strategic)

**Example (Notion SMB):** "Point solutions (Confluence for docs, Asana for tasks) create silos. Notion connects everything."

---

#### 7. Category Creation
**Claim:** "We created a new category: [category name]"

**When to use:**
- Existing categories don't fit what you do
- You're so different you need new language
- You can educate the market on new category

**Examples:**
- ✅ "We invented the 'Connected Workspace' - not a wiki, not a project tool, something new"
- ✅ "The first 'Revenue Operations Platform' category"
- ❌ "We're unique" (not category creation, just vague)

**What you need:**
- Budget to educate market on new category
- Willingness to define and defend category
- First-mover advantage

**Example (Notion SMB):** "All-in-one workspace" - not wiki, not project management, new category

